revision.text:
{{wide image|Effects of overscan on fixed-pixel displays.png|400px|The effects of overscan on fixed-pixel displays. View it at full size in order to see the effects.|300px|right}}
'''1:1 pixel mapping''' is a video display technique applicable to devices with native fixed [[pixels]], such as [[LCD monitor]]s and [[plasma display]]s. A monitor that has been set to 1:1 pixel mapping will display an input source without scaling it, such that each [[pixel]] received is mapped to a single native pixel on the monitor. This technique avoids loss of sharpness due to scaling artifacts and normally{{Efn|Except the uncommon case where display and input differ in [[pixel aspect ratio]] such as when one doesn't use [[square pixels]]}} avoids incorrect [[aspect ratio]] due to stretching. If the input [[Display resolution|resolution]] is less than the monitor's [[native resolution]], this will result in black borders around the image (e.g. [[letterboxing (filming)|letterboxing]] or [[windowboxing]]).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sayer|first1=Rob|title=Guide to Pixel Mapping|url=http://www.onstagelighting.co.uk/lighting-equipment/stage-lighting-control/guide-to-pixel-mapping/|website=onstagelighting.co.uk|accessdate=18 June 2015|date=17 February 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Drawbaugh|first1=Ben|title=Does your HDTV support 1:1 pixel mapping?|url=https://www.engadget.com/2007/08/20/does-your-hdtv-support-1-1-pixel-mapping/|website=Engadget|accessdate=18 June 2015|date=20 August 2007}}</ref>

